A new science
In this summer, an unusual conference took place in Paris. There, researchers gathered to contemplate the necessity of a new science, which could be just as revolutionary as Einstein's insights a hundred years ago.
The majority of scientists believe that the fundamental questions of the sciences have been answered.
In light of the great challenges, it is believed that there is little left to discover.
The remaining questions can be divided into three groups: First, the great unsolved mysteries of science (such as the unification of gravity and electricity in a theory), the exploration of which requires enormous investments and the infrastructure of the First World. Second, data collection, which refers to work related to archaeological excavations and biological/genetic studies, and third, problems whose solution must be based on scientific foundations, such as the fight against AIDS or global warming.
In addition, people are of the opinion that the only difficult part of the work would be to use already known natural laws with the help of new technologies for the benefit of humanity.
Who could deny that?
The models of today work, after all.
A growing group of scientists, however, points to phenomena that are not well explained by today's theories.
These problems occur more frequently, but are also cleverly circumvented, because there is simply no science with which these problems could be explained.
This missing science would describe processes and the emergence of entire systems.
In each individual scientific discipline, the knowledge is somewhat well established.
The physics, at least the part with which we ordinary people are confronted, is well researched.
Chemistry and biochemistry also stand on solid foundations – although there are still a few things in our body that we do not yet understand, it can be assumed that the basic mechanisms of interaction between cells and molecules are known.
Moreover, there are the new social sciences, which focus on people and societies.
In each of these fields – physics, biochemistry, and social sciences – the theories are well-established and largely uncontested.
Each discipline has its own language and its own mechanisms.
In the rarest of cases is a scientist an expert in more than one field, because these worlds and languages are simply so different.
This means that we cannot find answers to complex questions that require the involvement of multiple disciplines.
Take, for example, the brain.
This complex organ consists of molecules whose interaction is based on the principles of physics. The information conveyed is transmitted according to the laws of electricity.
Furthermore, there is a system of specialized cells that communicate through the exchange of chemical substances and also transmit information in this process.
When two brains interact, a new level is introduced: here, information exchange occurs through language, symbols, and concepts.
On each level, it is about the exchange of information, and there are appropriate theories that explain the processes on each individual level.
However, information is also exchanged between the individual levels, but there is no science that could even begin to explain this information exchange.
To compensate for this deficiency, some scientists have attempted to redefine the instruments for explaining processes within one level in order to apply them on another level.
These attempts then lead to something like a "language" at the cellular level and "energy" behind organized societies.
Sometimes this "transplantation" of explanatory patterns works quite well, but the fundamental problem remains unsolved: What is the nature of the information exchanged between the individual levels and how is it transmitted?
Now, almost all systems in the world consist of such levels.
And in all cases, there is this humiliating lack of knowledge about how the overall system functions.
The group of interdisciplinary scientists who gathered in Paris has loosely formed under the name "Foundations of Information Science."
The researchers come from various countries and fields and have been collaborating on a decentralized basis for eight years.
In addition to scientists from the relevant disciplines, art theorists, psychiatrists, language experts, and philosophers are beginning to participate in the discourse.
The majority of the group relies on this "transplantation strategy," in which the scientific foundations of one level are adapted and supplemented to be transferred to another level.
Others, on the other hand, consider a completely new approach to be necessary.
In their view, many scientific norms are the product of historical accidents and new ways of thinking are needed.
If the FIS group is lucky, new radical approaches emerge from scientists who currently lack access to the infrastructure of the First World.
Fully free thinking is an underestimated factor.
Almost all activities that take place under the banner of "science" have, much like their counterparts in the world of economics, developed an institutional character.
One believes that developing countries would have to build up similar resources as industrialized countries. This could however stifle creative thinking.
Many young scientists are currently experiencing a revolution, and many of these – sometimes revolutionary – ideas originate from laboratories and research centers that are not associated with major institutions.
The most sophisticated approaches in the field of mathematical algorithms came for twenty years from the Soviet Union, where there was a chronic shortage of computing capacity everywhere.
The most brilliant and in the truest sense of the word world-changing insights in the field of physics of recent decades did not come, as expected, from the well-known innovation centers, but from Budapest.
In Iran, there is an architectural tradition that has contributed to important insights for cognitive scientists.
And the most radical new ideas in the field of second-generation artificial intelligence (the so-called "autonomous agents") today come from Prague.
The most creative scientific achievements entered history.
When Einstein expanded physics with a new way of thinking, he changed the identity of space and time. The FIS conference in July was the unannounced beginning of an attempt to redefine the universe in this way.
Those gaps were identified that require explanations.
One is expected to include more scientists from innovative regions in this group in order to later identify those problems that could be solved once this new science is developed, or to discover them, as one might say.
